string.key: Our website uses cookies. A cookie is a small file of letters and numbers that we put on your computer if you agree. These cookies allow us to distinguish you from other users of the website which helps us to provide you with a good experience when you browse our website and also allows us to improve our site. For more information on cookies visit www.allaboutcookies.org. Cookies are not dangerous for your computer. We don't store any personally identifiable information about you on any of our cookies. Below you can check what cookies we use and opt out of them using the slider if needed:
string.tr: Notre site Web utilise des cookies. Un cookie est un petit fichier constitué de lettres et de chiffres que nous installons, si vous l’acceptez, sur votre ordinateur. Ces cookies nous permettent de vous distinguer des autres utilisateurs du site Web, ce qui nous permet de vous rendre la navigation plus agréable et d’améliorer notre site Web. Pour de plus amples informations sur les cookies, rendez-vous sur www.allaboutcookies.org. Les cookies ne sont pas dangereux pour votre ordinateur. Nous ne conservons aucune information privée identifiable vous concernant sur nos cookies. Vous pouvez consulter, ci-dessous, les cookies que nous utilisons, et les refuser en utilisant le curseur, si nécessaire :

Ces cookies expirent à l’issue de la session de navigation et ne sont donc pas conservés sur le long terme. Ces cookies ne peuvent pas être désactivés.

Go to the "Advanced tools -> Cron jobs" section from the cPanel main page. Choose "Standard" level. Enter your email address to the corresponding field in order to get notification when cron job runs. Enter the following text to the " Command to run" field:

Set "Minute(s)" to "0", "Hour(s)" to "0 = 12 AM/Midnight", "Day(s)" to "Every Day", "Month(s)" to "Every Month", "Weekday(s)" to "Every Weekday". Then click "Save Crontab" button. This cron job will run task scheduler every day at midnight. Notice: Cron job configuration interface may vary depending on control panel software and version used on your hosting server. To work with recurring billing in Authorize.Net you need to set the Silent Post URL. It is the URL where the subscription notifications will be sent.

The Silent Post URL is a location on your Web server where the payment gateway can "carbon copy" the transaction response. This allows you to use transaction response information for other purposes separately without affecting the amount of time it takes to respond to the payment gateway with a custom receipt page from the Relay Response URL.
To configure the Silent Post URL
Log on to the Merchant Interface at https://account.authorize.net
Click Settings under Account in the main menu on the left
Click Silent Post URL in the Transaction Format Settings section
Enter the secondary URL to which you would like the payment gateway to copy the transaction response
Go to Settings » API Login ID and Transaction Key. There you will get the 'Current API Login ID' and the 'Current Transaction Key' (copy them).
Also go to Settings » MD5-Hash. And enter any descired value for the MD5-Hash. (copy it).
Then you need to go to your SmartJobBoard Admin Panel » Payments » Authorize.Net SIM (edit) and specify there the API Login ID, Transaction Key and MD5-Hash.
